"""
MKT Context Commentary — Joshua chapters 12–14
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-joshua-12-14-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/joshua.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/joshua.json

Key decisions:
- Ch 12: Victory list as royal-annal genre; notes on major city-states.
- Ch 13: Unreduced territories treated as the honest tension in Joshua's conquest claim;
  Levi's landlessness as a distinctive theological arrangement.
- Ch 14: Caleb's Kenizzite identity; lot-casting as ANE legal procedure;
  Anakites as the specific giant-clan that caused the Kadesh crisis in Num 13-14.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOSHUA = {
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 12 is a summary victory list in the genre of royal annals — comparable to Egyptian and Assyrian campaign records that enumerate defeated kings and territories. Ancient Near Eastern kings marked military achievements this way; Joshua\'s list functions as a covenant document confirming YHWH\'s delivery of the land. It opens with the Transjordanian conquests (Moses\'s campaigns, Num 21) before listing the Cisjordanian conquests, presenting the full scope of the land-taking as a unified divine act.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Sihon king of the Amorites was the ruler of a significant kingdom centered at Heshbon in Transjordan. The Arnon River gorge formed the southern boundary between Sihon\'s territory and Moab. The defeat of Sihon (Num 21:21-31) was Israel\'s first military victory under Moses and established the pattern of divine-warrior conquest: Israel approached peacefully, was refused passage, and YHWH gave the victory. Sihon and Og become paradigmatic enemies in later biblical reflection (Neh 9:22; Ps 135:11; 136:19-20).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Arabah (the rift valley running from the Sea of Galilee south to the Dead Sea) and the Sea of Kinnereth (Galilee) mark the eastern territory\'s western extent. Beth-jeshimoth is near the Dead Sea\'s north end. The precise geographic notation is characteristic of ANE administrative texts — the boundary descriptions follow natural features (rivers, seas, mountain ridges) that served as recognized frontiers in the Bronze Age Levant.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Og king of Bashan is described as one of the last of the <em>Repha\'im</em> — the pre-Israelite giant populations of the region (cf. Gen 14:5; 15:20; Deut 3:11). Bashan (the Golan Heights region) was famous for its fertile plateau, oak forests, and cattle (Ps 22:12; Amos 4:1). Og\'s iron bed (Deut 3:11) — nine cubits long — was displayed as a trophy in Rabbah, a trophy of an extraordinary enemy. The Rephaim tradition reflects pre-Israelite Bronze Age populations whose physical distinctiveness became legendary.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Mount Hermon (2,814m) is the highest peak in the region, at the northern extent of Bashan\'s territory. The Geshurites and Maacathites are small Aramean kingdoms in the Hermon foothills. Significantly, these were <em>not</em> completely expelled (13:13) — they remain as enclaves within the conquered territory, an honest admission that the conquest was incomplete in some areas despite the idealized summary of 11:23.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Transjordanian kingdoms were given to the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and half of Manasseh — the Transjordanian inheritance requested in Num 32 and confirmed by Moses. The formula "Moses the servant of the LORD and the Israelites defeated them" establishes the covenantal continuity between Moses\'s campaigns and Joshua\'s: one divine conquest, two human agents. The phrase "servant of the LORD" (<em>eved YHWH</em>) is Moses\'s defining title throughout Joshua.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The list of Cisjordanian (west-Jordan) kings encompasses the full geographic range of the conquest: from Baal-gad in the Beqaa Valley (Lebanon) south to Mount Halak near the Negev. This north-south sweep follows the military campaigns of Joshua 6-11. The phrase "from Baal-gad below Mount Hermon to the bare mountain that goes up toward Seir" provides the book\'s geographic frame — the idealized maximal extent.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The six geographic zones — hill country, western foothills (<em>Shephelah</em>), Arabah, mountain slopes (<em>ashdot</em>), wilderness (<em>midbar</em>), and Negev — represent the full ecological range of Canaan. This sixfold list matches the geographic self-description of Joshua 11:16. The <em>Shephelah</em> (lowland foothills between the coastal plain and the Judean hills) was economically critical, controlling access to the highlands. The list of peoples displaced (Hittites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites, Hivites, Jebusites) corresponds to Exod 3:8\'s enumeration of land-holders.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Jericho was the first conquest and the gateway to the hill country — its fall (Josh 6) opened the central highlands to Israel\'s advance. Archaeological excavations at Tell es-Sultan (Jericho) show repeated destruction and abandonment cycles; the precise stratum corresponding to Joshua\'s conquest is debated between the Early Bronze, Middle Bronze, and Late Bronze periods. Ai (near modern Deir Dibwan, or possibly Khirbet el-Maqatir) is associated with Bethel — its king is listed together because the battle of Ai involved Bethel\'s king coming to assist (8:17).</p>',
    "10": '<p>Jerusalem (<em>Yerushalayim</em>) appears here as a defeated city-state, though the Jebusites retained actual control of the city until David\'s capture of it (2 Sam 5:6-9). The Jebusite stronghold on the ridge of Ophel was one of the last to fall. Hebron (Kiriath-arba) had been the home of the Anakites (Num 13:22), the giants who terrorized the spies at Kadesh-barnea; its conquest is specifically celebrated in Joshua 10:36-37 and is linked to Caleb\'s personal campaign (Josh 15:13-14).</p>',
    "11": '<p>Jarmuth and Lachish were members of the southern coalition (Josh 10:3-5) that formed against Israel after the fall of Jericho. Lachish (<em>Tell ed-Duweir</em>) was one of the most important cities in the Shephelah — a major Bronze Age fortification that commanded the western approaches to Jerusalem. Archaeological excavations at Lachish show substantial destruction levels from the Late Bronze Age consistent with the biblical narrative.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Eglon and Gezer were the last two members of the southern coalition. Gezer (<em>Tell Jezer</em>) was strategically positioned at the entrance to the Aijalon Valley — the road from the coastal plain to Jerusalem. Despite its defeat here, Gezer remained Canaanite until the Pharaoh of Egypt gave it as a dowry to his daughter at Solomon\'s marriage (1 Kgs 9:16). The continued Canaanite presence in key cities is typical of the partial conquest acknowledged throughout the book.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Debir (possibly Khirbet Rabud) was a hill-country city later specifically conquered by Othniel, Caleb\'s nephew (Josh 15:15-17; Judg 1:11-13). Its conquest by two agents — the initial campaign here and the tribal allotment campaign — illustrates how the book presents both the idealized conquest (all taken) and the ongoing reality (individual tribes must secure their portions). Geder is unidentified; many city-states in the Shephelah and hill country have not been definitively located archaeologically.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Hormah ("devoted to destruction") appears earlier in Numbers 14:45 and 21:3 as a place of Israelite defeat and then victory. Its inclusion in the Canaanite king-list here confirms that the named places in this chapter carry a history. Arad (<em>Tell Arad</em>) is one of the best-excavated Bronze Age sites in the Negev; its stratified remains have illuminated Israelite temple architecture and administrative practices in the Iron Age, though the Bronze Age city level shows the pre-Israelite occupation the list addresses.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Libnah was in the Shephelah; it later became a Levitical city and was briefly associated with a rebellion against Jehoram (2 Kgs 8:22). Adullam is famous as the location of David\'s cave during his flight from Saul (1 Sam 22:1) — the conquered Canaanite city became an Israelite refuge a generation later. The list of thirty-one kings demonstrates how thoroughly city-state culture organized Canaan: Bronze Age Canaan was a patchwork of semi-independent urban centers, each with its own king, unlike the tribal confederacy Israel was forming.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Makkedah was the site where five Canaanite kings hid in a cave after the battle of Gibeon (Josh 10:16-27) and were executed by Joshua. Bethel (modern Beitin) was a major religious center — Abraham had built an altar there (Gen 12:8; 13:3), and Jacob\'s dream of the heavenly ladder occurred at Bethel (Gen 28:11-19). Its conquest ended the Canaanite city-state phase, though Bethel later became the northern kingdom\'s main sanctuary under Jeroboam (1 Kgs 12:29) — the conquest did not prevent apostasy.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Tappuah is associated with the Manasseh-Ephraim boundary (17:7-8). Hepher (possibly in the Sharon Plain) is identified in the Solomonic administrative districts (1 Kgs 4:10). The list\'s pairing format — two kings per verse — reflects a standardized administrative enumeration. Twenty-four pairs of kings across vv.9-24 would yield twenty-four verses for the west-Jordan portion, matching the layout.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Aphek controlled the headwaters of the Yarkon River on the coastal plain. It appears repeatedly in Israelite history: the Philistines camped at Aphek before the battle in which the ark was captured (1 Sam 4:1), and it is mentioned in connection with Syrian wars (1 Kgs 20:26-30). The site (<em>Ras el-Ain / Tel Aphek</em>) has been extensively excavated, with significant Late Bronze Age Egyptian administrative remains confirming it as a regional center during the conquest period.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Madon and Hazor were members of the northern coalition (Josh 11:1). Hazor (<em>Tell el-Qedah</em>) was the dominant city in Bronze Age Canaan — the book itself calls it "formerly the head of all these kingdoms" (11:10). Archaeological excavations by Yigael Yadin (1955-1958, resumed 1990s) revealed a massive Bronze Age city of 200 acres with a population estimated at 40,000 — ten times larger than most Canaanite cities. A destruction layer in the 13th century BCE corresponds roughly to Joshua\'s campaign.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Shimron-meron and Achshaph were northern coalition members. The Jezreel Valley (near Megiddo) formed the northern battleground. Achshaph is possibly Tell Keisan near Acre. The northern campaign (Josh 11) was the most geographically distant from the Gilgal base camp and required the longest march, reflecting the scope of the divine commission ("all the land from the wilderness and Lebanon," 1:4).</p>',
    "21": '<p>Taanach and Megiddo were two of the most strategic sites in the entire land, guarding the passes through the Carmel ridge to the Jezreel Valley. Megiddo (<em>Tell Megiddo</em>) was one of the most excavated sites in Israel, with 26 occupation layers. The broad plain of Megiddo (Armageddon) was one of the ancient world\'s great battlefields; its strategic importance explains why it appears from Josh 12 through Rev 16:16. Despite listing Megiddo\'s king as defeated here, Manasseh failed to drive out Megiddo\'s inhabitants (Judg 1:27).</p>',
    "22": '<p>Kedesh in Galilee later became one of the six cities of refuge (Josh 20:7) and a Levitical city (21:32). Jokneam in Carmel controlled another pass through the Carmel ridge. The recurrence of these cities throughout Joshua — in the king-list, in tribal allotments, as Levitical cities, as cities of refuge — shows how the book builds a coherent geographic picture of the whole land as covenant inheritance.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Dor on the Carmel coast (modern Tantura) was a major Bronze Age port city; Egyptian records mention it as a Sea Peoples settlement. The "region of Dor" reflects its status as a coastal subdistrict. Goiim in Gilgal is uncertain — possibly a reference to the mixed population that characterized certain areas. The coastal cities were among the most difficult to incorporate into Israelite settlement, given their Phoenician and Philistine connections.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Tirzah became the first capital of the northern kingdom after Solomon\'s death (1 Kgs 14:17; 15:21). Its position in this list places it among the original Canaanite city-states of the hill country. The total of thirty-one kings for the Cisjordanian campaign (added to the two Transjordanian kings = thirty-three total) is likely a schematic number reflecting the thoroughness of the divine conquest. The closing formula — "in all, thirty-one kings" — is the kind of administrative summary found on Egyptian and Mesopotamian victory steles.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>The tension between Josh 11:23 ("Joshua took all the land") and 13:1 ("a great deal of land remains to be taken") is resolved by recognizing two levels of description: the overall military defeat of organized Canaanite resistance (complete) and the actual settlement of the population (incomplete). This is standard in ANE conquest accounts — Thutmose III\'s Annals claim all of Canaan while Egyptian records show ongoing Canaanite city-state activity. Joshua is old (<em>zaqen</em>) and "advanced in years" — the appointment of his successor\'s task is urgent.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The Philistines (<em>Pelishtim</em>) are listed as unreduced territory — ironic, since the five Philistine city-states (Gaza, Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gath, Ekron) would become Israel\'s greatest military challenge in the period of the judges and early monarchy. The Philistines (likely part of the Sea Peoples migrations of the 12th century BCE) were not yet the dominant coastal power during Joshua\'s conquest; this list anticipates the situation that developed later. The Geshurites here are not the Transjordanian Geshurites of 13:11 but a Negev-region group.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Shihor east of Egypt is likely the easternmost branch of the Nile delta or the Wadi el-Arish — the traditional southwestern boundary of Canaan. Ekron is the northernmost of the five Philistine cities. The five Philistine lords (<em>sarnei Pelishtim</em>) used the distinctive term <em>seren</em> (a non-Semitic word, possibly related to Greek <em>tyrannos</em>), reflecting the Philistines\' non-Semitic origin. Avvim are a pre-Philistine coastal population displaced by the Philistines (Deut 2:23).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The Sidonians controlled the Phoenician coast (modern Lebanon). Aphek at the border of the Amorites in the north is different from the Aphek in the Sharon Plain. The northern coastal and Lebanese territories remained unconquered throughout the period of the judges and were never fully incorporated into Israel\'s territory. Tyre and Sidon remained independent Phoenician cities that maintained commercial and diplomatic relations with Israel (Solomon\'s alliance with Hiram, 1 Kgs 5).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The Giblites (Gebalites) are the inhabitants of Byblos (<em>Gebal</em>), the ancient Phoenician port city famous for its cedar trade and as the origin of the word "Bible" (via <em>byblos</em>, papyrus/book). Lebanon remained outside Israelite control throughout the entire period. Lebo-hamath (the entrance to Hamath, modern Lebweh on the Orontes) was the traditional northern boundary of the ideal Israelite territory (Num 34:8; 1 Kgs 8:65).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Misrephoth-maim (possibly Tell Mushrefeh near the coast) marked the northeastern extent of Joshua\'s northern campaign (Josh 11:8). The divine promise "<em>I</em> will drive out" (first person singular, divine) for the remaining territories distinguishes them from the territories Joshua has already taken. The promise is not retracted — YHWH will complete what Joshua began — but it will require the tribes to continue under divine direction. The book\'s theology allows for human failure to complete the task without withdrawing the divine promise.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The nine and a half tribes east of the Jordan receive their allotments through the lot-casting process (14:2). The half-tribe of Manasseh is distributed on both sides of the Jordan: half east (13:29-31) and half west (17:1-13), reflecting the pragmatic administrative result of their territory request (Num 32) and their large family structure (Num 26:28-37). The land division is framed as a divine command, not merely a political arrangement.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The Reubenites and Gadites had secured their inheritance east of the Jordan under Moses (Num 32). Their Transjordanian territory (essentially modern Jordan) was outside the boundaries of the Promised Land as defined in Num 34, but within the territory that YHWH had given Israel through military conquest. The text carefully distinguishes this Mosaic grant from the Canaan distribution Joshua oversees.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Aroer on the Arnon gorge is a key boundary marker that recurs throughout the Transjordanian boundary descriptions (Deut 2:36; 3:12; Josh 12:2; 13:16). The Arnon River (Wadi Mujib) cuts dramatically through the plateau into the Dead Sea — a natural geographic boundary between Moab to the south and the Amorite kingdom to the north. Medeba (modern Madaba) was a significant Transjordanian city that appears in the Mesha Stele (the Moabite Stone), an extra-biblical inscription from ca. 840 BCE that confirms and complicates the biblical account of Israelite-Moabite relations.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The cities of Sihon\'s kingdom in the plateau of Heshbon describe a well-established urban network in the Transjordanian highlands. The boundary with Ammon (<em>bnei Ammon</em>) reflects ongoing tensions between Israel and Ammon that continue throughout the judges period (Judg 10-11) and into the monarchy (1 Sam 11; 2 Sam 10). The Ammonite prohibition against entering the assembly (Deut 23:3) reflects this hostile relationship.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Gilead — the forested highland east of the Jordan between the Yarmuk and Arnon rivers — was shared between the tribes and the remaining Geshurite and Maacathite enclaves. The explicit note that these peoples were <em>not</em> expelled (v.13) is significant: the conquest narrative does not conceal incomplete obedience. Gilead later becomes the home of Elijah (1 Kgs 17:1) and is famous for its healing balm (Jer 8:22).</p>',
    "12": '<p>The Rephaim connection for both Og and the Rephaim of Bashan places these pre-Israelite populations in the context of the Bronze Age giant-traditions of the Levant. Bashan\'s royal cities of Ashtaroth (Tell Ashtara) and Edrei (modern Deraa) controlled the northern Transjordanian plateau. The Deir Alla inscription (8th century BCE) from the Jordan Valley mentions Balaam son of Beor in an Aramaic text — providing extra-biblical confirmation of the Balaam tradition in this region.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The failure to drive out the Geshurites and Maacathites "to this day" is a candid editorial note — they remain as enclaves within Israelite-controlled territory throughout the period of writing. Geshur became significant in David\'s history: he married the daughter of Talmai king of Geshur (2 Sam 3:3), and his son Absalom fled there after killing Amnon (2 Sam 13:37-38). The unconquered territory created ongoing complications for later Israelite history.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The Levitical non-inheritance is stated here and repeated emphatically in v.33. Levi\'s landlessness was distinctive among ancient peoples — most priestly classes controlled temple estates. The explanation "<em>the offerings made by fire to the LORD God of Israel are their inheritance</em>" (<em>ishei YHWH</em>) means Levi\'s sustenance comes from the sacrificial system — the portions given to priests from every offering. This theology of divine provision rather than land possession becomes a model for NT thinking about Christian community and support of ministry (1 Cor 9:13-14).</p>',
    "15": '<p>The allotments to Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh occupy much of the chapter and are given in the same formulaic structure: "Moses gave an inheritance to... according to their clans." The formulaic repetition (vv.15, 24, 29) emphasizes that this distribution has the same divine authority as the Cisjordanian distribution Joshua oversees. The Transjordanian tribes are full covenant members, not second-class Israelites with a lesser inheritance.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The plateau (<em>mishor</em>) of Medeba in Reuben\'s territory was a flat tableland suitable for agriculture and herding. Aroer marks the southern boundary; the Arnon gorge defined the physical border with Moab. The Mesha Stele (ca. 840 BCE) mentions that Reuben occupied Medeba and Aroer, then Moab recovered them — providing external evidence that this region was genuinely contested between Israelite and Moabite populations throughout the Iron Age.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Dibon (<em>Dhiban</em>) is where the Mesha Stele was discovered in 1868. Bamoth-baal (Heights of Baal) was a high place where Balak took Balaam to curse Israel (Num 22:41) — the conquest territory includes the very sites of attempted opposition to Israel\'s advance. Beth-baal-meon (Beth-meon) is a recurring Moabite town mentioned in Jer 48:23 and Ezek 25:9, indicating ongoing Moabite presence in this area despite Reubenite settlement.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Jahaz was the site of Sihon\'s battle against Israel (Num 21:23; Deut 2:32) — the definitive engagement that established Israelite control of the Transjordanian plateau. The city later became a Levitical city (Josh 21:36). Kedemoth is identified with Salhiya in Jordan. Mephaath appears in Jer 48:21 as a Moabite city, again illustrating the contested nature of this territory across generations.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Kiriathaim (Qaryatein) appears in both pre-Israelite and post-conquest lists — it was originally Emim territory (Gen 14:5) and appears as a Moabite town in Jer 48:1, 23 and Ezek 25:9. Sibmah was famous for its vineyards (Isa 16:8-9; Jer 48:32). Zereth-shahar on the hill above the valley is unidentified. The inclusion of these specific small towns shows that the allotment process involved detailed local knowledge of the Transjordanian landscape.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Beth-peor was directly across from Moses\'s burial site (Deut 3:29; 4:46; 34:6) and near the valley of Moab where Israel camped before crossing into Canaan. It was associated with the Baal Peor apostasy (Num 25). Pisgah is the ridge from which Moses saw the Promised Land (Deut 3:27; 34:1). Beth-jeshimoth (near the Dead Sea\'s northeast shore) marked the boundary with Moab. The Reubenite territory thus encompasses the final wilderness campsites — the transition zone between wilderness and the land.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The five Midianite princes — Evi, Rekem, Zur, Hur, and Reba — were killed in the campaign of Numbers 31, the same campaign that killed Balaam. They are described here as "princes of Sihon" — their relationship to Sihon\'s kingdom shows how the Midianite leadership was intertwined with the Amorite political structure in the region. The campaign against Midian (Num 31) and the defeat of Sihon (Num 21) are thus historically and politically connected.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Balaam son of Beor, "the diviner" (<em>haqqosem</em>), was killed by the Israelites in this campaign. The use of <em>qosem</em> (diviner, one who practices <em>qesem</em> — divination by lots or arrows) rather than <em>navi</em> (prophet) is evaluative: despite speaking genuine divine oracles (Num 22-24), Balaam is remembered as a professional diviner who ultimately used his knowledge for personal gain (the Balaam episodes end with his complicity in the Baal Peor apostasy, Num 31:16). His death in the conquest is the closure of a narrative that began in Num 22.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The Jordan forms the western boundary of Reuben\'s territory — the river that separates the Promised Land from the Transjordanian possession. The closing formula "this was the inheritance of the Reubenites according to their clans" (<em>lemishpechotam</em>) marks the administrative closure of one tribal allotment. The word <em>nachala</em> (inheritance) carries both legal and theological weight: it is a permanent family possession granted by divine authority, not merely a military acquisition.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Gad\'s territory in Gilead occupied the central Transjordanian highlands — the forested plateau between the Yarmuk and Jabbok rivers. Gilead\'s forests and pastures made it suitable for the "large amounts of livestock" that motivated the Reubenite and Gadite request for Transjordanian land (Num 32:1-5). The region\'s relative isolation from the tribal heartland contributed to tensions between Transjordanian and Cisjordanian Israel in later periods (cf. the Jephthah-Ephraim conflict, Judg 12:1-6; and the Jabesh-Gilead episodes, Judg 21; 1 Sam 31:11-13).</p>',
    "25": '<p>Jazer (possibly Khirbet Jazzir) and the Ammonite territory mark Gad\'s eastern boundary. The formula "half the land of the Ammonites" reflects a boundary settlement that acknowledged Ammonite claims east of Gad\'s territory. Aroer east of Rabbah (Ammon, modern Amman) is different from the Aroer on the Arnon — the territory contains multiple places with similar names, a common feature of Semitic toponymy where descriptive terms (like Aroer = "bare/stripped") were applied to similar landscapes in different regions.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Ramath-mizpah (possibly Tell er-Rameh in Gilead) was a strategic highland site — <em>mitspa</em> (watchtower/lookout) reflects its defensive position. The Jabbok River (Wadi Zarqa) was where Jacob wrestled the angel (Gen 32:22-32), making the Gadite territory historically resonant for Israel\'s ancestral traditions. Mahanaim (two camps) was where Jacob met the angels (Gen 32:1-2) and later served as David\'s refuge from Absalom (2 Sam 17:24, 27) — the landscape of the allotment carries patriarchal memory.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The valley (<em>emek</em>) cities of Beth-haram, Succoth, and Zaphon were in the Jordan Valley lowland, distinct from the Gilead highlands. Succoth is the first campsite after Jacob\'s Jabbok crossing (Gen 33:17) — Jacob built booths (<em>sukkot</em>) there, giving the place its name. The Jordan Valley portion of Gad\'s inheritance thus includes the land of Jacob\'s own return journey — the patriarchal geography is being reclaimed by Jacob\'s descendants.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The closing formula for Gad repeats the administrative pattern of v.23. The emphasis on "towns and their surrounding villages" (<em>arim uvaroteihem</em>) reflects the ANE settlement pattern of a fortified central city surrounded by dependent agricultural villages — the city-state model translated into tribal territory. Each inheritance includes both the urban centers and the agricultural hinterland that sustained them.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The half-tribe of Manasseh east of the Jordan received Bashan — the northern plateau extending from the Yarmuk to Mount Hermon. The half-tribe arrangement (with the other half receiving Cisjordanian territory in Josh 17) created a geographically divided tribe, which raised questions about tribal solidarity. Manasseh was Joseph\'s firstborn son (Gen 48), and the two half-tribe territories together constituted the largest single tribal inheritance.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Mahanaim is the northern boundary of Gad\'s territory and the southern boundary of Manasseh\'s — the two Josephite half-tribes shared a border in Transjordan. "All of Bashan" including the sixty towns of Jair (the <em>Havvoth-jair</em>, settlements established by Jair son of Manasseh, Num 32:41; Deut 3:14) reflects the earlier Israelite settlement of Bashan during Moses\'s campaigns. The sixty towns figure appears also in 1 Kgs 4:13 in the Solomonic administrative districts, suggesting continuity of this territorial designation into the monarchy.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The half of Gilead shared between the two Manassite half-tribes reflects a geographic division that distinguished Highland Gilead (forested, fertile) from the Bashan plateau. The descendants of Makir son of Manasseh (the primary Manassitesubgrouping in Num 26:29; 27:1) received the royal cities of Og. Makir appears earlier as a military leader in Num 32:39-40, taking Gilead in the initial Mosaic campaigns.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"The plains of Moab across the Jordan from Jericho" was Israel\'s final wilderness camp — the site of Moses\'s farewell speeches (Deuteronomy), the Baal Peor apostasy (Num 25), and the Transjordanian allotments (Num 32). The closing formula for the Mosaic distribution connects it geographically to the Deuteronomic setting, tying Joshua\'s administrative work back to its Mosaic foundation.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The repetition of Levi\'s non-inheritance ("the LORD God of Israel is their inheritance, as he said to them") closes the Transjordanian section with the theological key to the entire allotment system. YHWH is Israel\'s ultimate landlord; he distributes the land according to his own purposes. Levi alone lives by direct divine provision — their "inheritance" is YHWH himself — making them a paradigm of what the whole nation is called to: to find its security in the divine presence rather than territorial possession.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>The transition to Cisjordanian distribution introduces the administrative leadership: Eleazar the high priest and Joshua are the joint overseers, with the tribal heads assisting. Eleazar\'s role as the priestly leader alongside Joshua (the military-civil leader) models the division of authority between religious and political leadership that characterized early Israel\'s governance. The formula "the Israelites received as their inheritance in Canaan, distributed by Eleazar the priest and Joshua son of Nun" establishes both the religious legitimacy and the legal completeness of the process.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The lot (<em>goral</em>) casting was a sacred divination procedure understood as revealing YHWH\'s will directly (Prov 16:33: "the lot is cast in the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD"). In the ANE, lots were used for land distribution, judicial decisions, military conscription, and priestly roster assignments. The lot-casting at Shiloh (18:1-10) is described in detail. The procedure removes human favoritism from the allotment — each tribe receives what YHWH apportions, not what political negotiation could secure.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The statement "Moses had already given the inheritance of the two and a half tribes on the east side of the Jordan, but to the Levites he gave no inheritance" is a summary bridge connecting what has been narrated (ch.13) to what follows (chs.14-21). The administrative clarity of this verse — accounting for all twelve tribes systematically — reflects the careful record-keeping of the distribution process.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The explanation for how twelve-tribe Israel distributes land among effectively thirteen territorial units (Joseph\'s double portion as Ephraim and Manasseh, with Levi receiving none) is addressed here. The double portion (<em>pi shenayim</em>) for Joseph\'s sons (Gen 48:5) was Jacob\'s death-bed grant elevating Joseph\'s sons to tribal status. This fulfilled the birthright blessing that Reuben forfeited (1 Chr 5:1-2). The Levitical towns (forty-eight cities, Josh 21) scattered throughout all tribal territories substitute for territorial inheritance.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The Israelites did as the LORD commanded Moses, and they partitioned the land." This simple summary verse functions as a compliance formula — the same structure as "and Moses did as the LORD commanded" throughout Exodus and Numbers. The theological point is that the land distribution is not Israel\'s achievement but YHWH\'s command executed faithfully. The entire allotment process is framed as obedience to the Mosaic mandate (Num 26:52-56; 34:13-15).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Caleb\'s approach to Joshua at Gilgal is presented as a private petition, separate from the formal lot-casting. The Kenizzite identity (<em>Qenizi</em>) is notable: the Kenizzites were listed among the pre-Israelite peoples of Canaan (Gen 15:19) and appear to have been an Edomite clan (Gen 36:11, 15) later absorbed into the tribe of Judah. Caleb\'s foreign origin did not diminish his status as one of the twelve spies or as the representative of Judah — his faith qualified him regardless of ethnic origin.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Caleb\'s age at Kadesh-barnea — forty years old when Moses sent him to spy (Num 13:6) — and the timeframe that follows establish the forty-five-year gap: forty years of wilderness wandering (Deut 2:14) plus five years of conquest campaigns. His "wholehearted" following (<em>male acharei YHWH</em>) is the phrase used of him in Num 14:24 and 32:12 — <em>male</em> (full/complete) describing the quality of his faithfulness in contrast to the other ten spies\' halfheartedness. His honest report at Kadesh despite the pressure of the majority is the act he recalls.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"My fellow scouts made the people\'s courage fail (<em>hemisu et lev ha\'am</em>, melted the heart of the people)." The ten unfaithful spies\' report (Num 13:26-33) used the terrifying description of Anakite giants that caused the congregation to weep and propose returning to Egypt (Num 14:1-4). Caleb\'s counter-testimony — "we should go up at once" (Num 13:30) — was drowned out by the majority. His faithfulness at that moment of crisis, against enormous social pressure, is the ground on which Moses\'s oath was made.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Moses\'s oath on that day at Kadesh-barnea is recorded in Deut 1:36: "The land on which your feet have trodden shall be an inheritance for you and your children forever, because you have wholly followed the LORD my God." The specific inheritance promised — Hebron and its surrounding territory — was the land Caleb had personally scouted, the Anakite heartland he was not afraid of. The forty-five-year wait between promise and fulfillment tests whether the promise is remembered and trusted.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"The LORD has kept me alive (<em>hecheyani</em>)" — the divine preservation of Caleb\'s life for forty-five years is itself evidence of covenant faithfulness. In the wilderness, the entire generation above twenty died except Caleb and Joshua (Num 14:29-30). Caleb\'s survival is not accidental but the direct fulfillment of the Num 14:24 promise: "my servant Caleb, because he has a different spirit... I will bring into the land." His survival through forty-five years of wilderness and warfare is the ongoing sign of divine faithfulness.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"I am still as strong (<em>chazaq</em>) today as I was when Moses sent me." Caleb at 85 claims the same physical strength as at 40. The word <em>chazaq</em> (strong) echoes the book\'s keynote command (hazaq we\'emats, 1:6-9) — Caleb embodies what Joshua was commanded to be. His strength "for battle and for every activity" (both military and productive) is presented as a sign of divine blessing on his faithfulness, not merely physical constitution. The claim is remarkable within the Bible\'s realistic portrayal of aging.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Give me this hill country that the LORD promised that day! You yourself heard how the Anakites were there with great, fortified cities." The Anakites (<em>Anakim</em>) were the specific giant-clan whose presence at Hebron (Num 13:22, 28, 33) had caused the greatest terror among the ten faithless spies — they are the very men Caleb refused to fear at Kadesh. His request for Hebron is a deliberate return to face the enemy he was unafraid of forty-five years earlier. The Anakite cities (<em>arim gedolot uvtsurot</em>, great and fortified cities) were the obstacle that defeated the courage of a generation; Caleb requests them as his personal inheritance.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Joshua\'s blessing of Caleb (<em>vayevarekhehu Yehoshua</em>) is a formal bestowal — a benediction with official force, like a father blessing a son or a king investing a vassal. The gift of Hebron as Caleb\'s personal inheritance is both a covenant fulfillment (Moses\'s oath) and a recognition of exemplary faith. Hebron (Kiriath-arba) was one of the most significant cities in Canaan — Abraham had purchased the cave of Machpelah there (Gen 23), and the patriarchs were buried there. It would later become David\'s first capital (2 Sam 2:1-4).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Hebron has belonged to Caleb son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite as his inheritance to this day, because he wholly followed the LORD God of Israel." The "to this day" formula marks the tradition as a living memory at the time of writing — Caleb\'s family still held Hebron. The Kenizzite reminder at the close of the account re-emphasizes that Caleb\'s Gentile origin did not disqualify him from full covenant inheritance. His inclusion is the OT\'s clearest demonstration that covenant faithfulness, not ethnic purity, determines one\'s portion in Israel\'s inheritance.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Kiriath-arba ("city of Arba") is named for Arba, described in the book as "the greatest of the Anakites" (<em>adam hagadol baAnaqim</em>). Arba appears also in Josh 15:13 and 21:11. The renaming of Kiriath-arba as Hebron (<em>chebron</em>, from <em>chaver</em>, companion/ally) may reflect the city\'s role as a covenant meeting place. The chapter closes with the phrase "and the land had rest from war" (<em>vatishqot ha\'arets mimilchamah</em>) — the same formula used at Josh 11:23. Rest from war is the temporal sign of covenant blessing in Joshua; the eschatological rest of Hebrews 4 is its permanent fulfillment.</p>'
  }
}

